Category Brand image belief Initial agreement (%) Repeated agreement (%)
Fast food outlets Good for a snack 29 56
Banks Progressive 22 47
Banks Expert in the areas it deals in 21 48
Insurance Provides fast service 17 42
Supermarket Sells low-quality fruit 14 36
Liquor/spirits Unique 10 36
summary_markdown: This data presents a comparative analysis of brand image beliefs across different service categories, specifically contrasting initial agreement percentages with repeated agreement percentages. For fast food outlets, the belief "Good for a snack" shows a significant increase from 29% initial to 56% repeated agreement. Banks exhibit similar patterns, with "Progressive" rising from 22% to 47% and "Expert in the areas it deals in" from 21% to 48%. Insurance sees a substantial jump for "Provides fast service" from 17% to 42%. Supermarkets, with the belief "Sells low-quality fruit," move from 14% to 36% repeated agreement. Finally, liquor/spirits, under the belief "Unique," also demonstrates growth from 10% to 36% repeated agreement. The overarching structure highlights how repeated exposure or experience with a brand can positively influence consumer perception, often more than initial impressions, across diverse industries.
